relation: Harbour service in 1910. Navigation school ship in September 1919, renamed Dryad. Sold for breaking in October 1924
Believed foundered with all hands after leaving Singapore for Shanghai on 10 September 1887
Sold at Sydney for breaking in 1905
Renamed Cockatrice in June 1896 and sold at Chatham on 3 April 1906

TableContextTimeStampAfterTable: {77691=The only ironclads of gunboat size were three largely experimental (and unsuccessful) vessels ordered in 1864. The first two were towed to Bermuda (being considered unsatisfactory to sail under their own power) where they served as harbour vessels. Vixen was the first twin-screw vessel built for the Royal Navy, and Waterwitch employed a form of water pump propulsion., 63112=The gunboats designed from 1870 onwards were of composite construction, i.e. they had an iron keel, stem and stern posts, and iron framing, with wooden planking retained over the iron frames., 115607=This section includes two early iron-hulled screw gunvessels of the 1840s, which in other respects were half-sisters to the wooden-hulled gunvessels ordered in 1846., 137343=The gunvessels designed from 1867 onwards were of composite construction, i.e. they had an iron keel, stem and stern posts, and iron framing, with wooden planking retained over the iron frames.}
